## Output Requirements

### HTML Structure
- Generate complete, valid HTML5 document with proper DOCTYPE
- Include appropriate `<head>` section with title and basic styling
- Use semantic HTML elements (`<article>`, `<section>`, `<header>`, `<main>`, etc.)
- Preserve document hierarchy with proper heading levels (`<h1>`, `<h2>`, `<h3>`, etc.)

### Content Preservation
- **Text Accuracy**: Maintain exact text content, including technical terms, citations, and references
- **Mathematical Content**: Convert equations to HTML entities, MathML, or descriptive text as appropriate
- **Tables**: Preserve table structure using proper `<table>`, `<thead>`, `<tbody>`, `<tr>`, `<th>`, `<td>` markup
- **Lists**: Convert bulleted and numbered lists to `<ul>` and `<ol>` with appropriate `<li>` elements
- **Formatting**: Preserve important formatting like bold, italic, and emphasis using `<strong>`, `<em>`, etc.

### Academic Document Handling
- **Multi-column Layout**: Read content in logical order (left-to-right, top-to-bottom)
- **Citations and References**: Maintain citation formatting and reference lists
- **Abstract and Keywords**: Mark up abstract sections appropriately
- **Author Information**: Preserve author names, affiliations, and contact information
- **Figures and Captions**: Include figure references and captions (note: actual images may not be extractable)

### Layout and Styling
- Include basic CSS styling in `<style>` tags for:
  - Typography (readable fonts, appropriate line spacing)
  - Table formatting (borders, padding, alignment)
  - Section spacing and hierarchy
  - Page layout and margins
- Ensure the HTML renders clearly in browsers
- Use responsive design principles for different screen sizes

### Quality Standards
- **Completeness**: Include all visible text content from the PDF
- **Accuracy**: Maintain exact spelling, punctuation, and technical terminology
- **Structure**: Reflect the document's logical organization and hierarchy
- **Readability**: Ensure the HTML version is as readable as the original PDF

## Content Processing Guidelines

### Headers and Footers
{% if singlePageOnly %}
- Include page headers/footers if they contain important content
{% else %}
- Ignore repetitive page numbers, running headers, and standard footers
- Include headers/footers only if they contain unique, important content
{% endif %}

### Special Elements
- **URLs and Links**: Convert to clickable `<a>` tags where appropriate
- **Email Addresses**: Format as `mailto:` links
- **Code Snippets**: Use `<pre>` and `<code>` tags for code blocks
- **Footnotes**: Include footnotes inline or in a separate section

### Error Handling
- If any content is unclear or ambiguous, make the best interpretation
- For complex mathematical expressions, provide both symbolic and descriptive text
- If tables are complex, prioritize data accuracy over perfect formatting

## Output Format
Return only the complete HTML document, starting with `<!DOCTYPE html>` and ending with `</html>`. Do not include any explanatory text before or after the HTML.